<DOC><DOCNO> AP880611-0156 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-11-88 2346EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0605 06-11 1187</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0605,1230</SECOND><NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with Belasco, Allen obits; AMs separate on Saragatmoved as a0594.</NOTE><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><BYLINE>Giuseppe Saragat</BYLINE><DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Giuseppe Saragat, Italy's first socialist president,died at home Saturday from a heart ailment. He was 89.   A founder of the Social Democratic Party and a staunchanti-communist, he joined the Socialist Party in 1922. He went intoexile in Austria and then France when dictator Benito Mussolinirose to power in 1926.   Years later, in 1947, he broke with the Socialist Party andformed the Social Democratic Party as a pro-Western, anti-communistforce.   During his seven years as the fifth president of the Republic,beginning in 1964, Saragat worked for reforms in housing, medicalcare, education and taxation.   Saragat was born Sept. 19, 1898, in Turin and obtained auniversity degree in economics and commerce. He worked as a bankclerk and for a newspaper and wrote political books under the penname ``Togaraso.''   He was elected to Parliament four times and served three timesas deputy premier. Saragat supported the Socialist-ChristianDemocrat alliance that governed Italy during six of his seven yearsas president.   Saragat engineered the merger of his party with the biggerSocialist Party in 1966, but when the unified party took a beatingin the 1968 elections the two again separated.   Saragat is survived by his son and daughter.</TEXT><BYLINE>Leon Belasco</BYLINE><DATELINE>ORANGE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Leon Belasco, a Russian immigrant whoparlayed his comedic talents and ability to do a range of foreignaccents into a career as a charactor actor spanning four decades,died June 1 at age 85.   Belasco, born in Odessa, Russia, in 1902, appeared in scores ofmovies, including ``Topper Takes a Trip,'' in 1939 and ``TheRussians Are Coming, The Russians are Coming,'' in 1966.   He generally played excitable characters, frequently appearingas a head waiter, landlord or ballet master.   Born Leonid Simeonovich Berladsky, Belasco began his career as aviolinist and orcehstra leader, working with the Andrews Sisters in1936. His movie career took off in 1939 when he won small roles inseveral films.   Among the better known movies he appeared in over the years were``Broadway Serenade in 1939, ``Holiday Inn,'' with Bing Crosby andFred Astaire, in 1942, and ``Casablanca,'' with Humphrey Bogart andIngrid Bergman, also in 1942.</TEXT><BYLINE>Byron Allen</BYLINE><DATELINE>DETROIT LAKES, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Byron G. Allen, former assistant toU.S. Commissioner of Agriculture Orville Freeman and a key figurein the merger of the Democratic and Farmer-Labor parties, diedFriday at the age of 86.   Allen, the DFL's first candidate for governor in 1944, was theMinnesota national Democratic committeeman from 1948 to 1955.   A native of Iowa, Allen was elected to the Iowa Legislature atage 25 and served there until 1932. In 1933 he became secretary ofthe Iowa Senate. He was director of the Iowa Old Age AssistanceSystem, a predecessor to the Social Security system, from 1934 to1939.   He and his family moved in 1940 to Detroit Lakes, where hecontinued a farm management and insurance business founded by hisgrandfather.   Allen was a member of the fusion committee that met in June 1944to found Minnesota's Democratic-Farmer-Labor party. Hubert H.Humphrey was the chief spokesman for the fusion Democrats.   A few months later, Humphrey managed Allen's campaign as theDFL's first candidate for governor. Allen lost to Republican EdwardJ. Thye.   Allen gave one of the 17 speeches nominating Franklin D.Roosevelt for president in 1944.   In 1955, Allen was appointed Minnesota Commissioner ofAgriculture and left the post to become assistant U.S. secretary ofAgriculture in 1961.   He returned to Detroit Lakes in 1969 and continued the familybusiness until retiring about three years ago.   Survivors include a son, a daughter, a sister and fivegrandchildren.</TEXT><HEAD>Helen Musgrove</HEAD><DATELINE>WESTMINSTER, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Helen ``Patches'' Musgrove, a VietnamWar correspondent and registered nurse who operated a shelter forChinese refugees, died Tuesday of pneumonia after a stroke. She was69.   Mrs. Musgrove worked as a war correspondent in the late 1960sand early 1970s after persuading a Florida newspaper to hire hereven though she had no newspaper reporting experience.   Her career in Asia began after the death of her husband, whenshe traveled to Hong Kong, opened a dress manufacturing plant andsold designer clothes to U.S. customers. She also opened a shelterfor Chinese refugees in Hong Kong.   Mrs. Musgrove went to Vietnam in 1966 and became a correspondentafter receiving the sponsorship of the Jacksonville (Fla.) Journal.For 6{ years she covered the war, entertained U.S. servicemen andhelped with medical needs.</TEXT><BYLINE>Josep Tarradellas</BYLINE><DATELINE>BARCELONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Josep Tarradellas, one of the fewremaining figures of Spain's 1936-39 Second Republic and formerhead of the autonomous Catalonian government, died Friday from achronic lung ailment. He was 89.   When he fled Spain in 1939, Tarradellas vowed never to set footin the country until Catalonian autonomy had been restored.   Tarradellas was the last major Republican exile to return toSpain after the death of dictator Gen. Francisco Franco in November1975. He came back in 1977.   Under Spain's 1978 constitution that restored democracy,Catalonia recovered its autonomous status lost when Franco's forcesemerged victorious in the 1936-39 Spanish Civil War.   King Juan Carlos named Tarradellas head of the Catalonianautonomous government of Generalitat in 1979. He retired frompolitics in 1980.</TEXT><BYLINE>Herman Crook</BYLINE><DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Herman Crook, a harmonica player who wasthe oldest member of the Grand Ole Opry, died Friday of respiratoryfailure after suffering a heart attack. He was 89.   Crook was the last remaining charter member of the Grand OleOpry, founded in 1925. He returned to the Opry last weekend after anine-week absence due to health problems.   In 1926, Crook led a country music string band on the SaturdayNight Barn Dance and went on the Opry in 1927. The band is the onlyact left that represents the original tradition of the Opry. Theband plays for cloggers, who perform traditional mountain dancing.   Crook was among the Opry musicians who participated inNashville's first recording sessions in 1928. By the 1960s, theOpry had become a modern, highly professional program, and thetraditional sound of Crook's group, the Crook Brothers Band, becamea less prominent part of the show.</TEXT><BYLINE>James H. Anderson</BYLINE><DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   James H. ``Andy'' Anderson, a former chiefof bureau for The Associated Press, died Thursday. He was 84.   Anderson, a native of Independence, Kan., joined the AP inKansas City in 1927. He transferred to St. Louis in 1935, and laterbecame chief of bureau in Oklahoma City from 1944-46.   Anderson continued to work in Oklahoma City until his retirementin 1968.   Stanley M. Swinton, assistant general manager of the AP at thetime of Anderson's retirement, said in 1968 of Anderson's work inOklahoma City that ``much of the bureau's success in that periodhad been the result'' of his efforts.   Memorial services for Anderson are scheduled for Saturday atFirst Presbyterian Church in Oklahoma City.</TEXT></DOC>